Utah HPV vaccine Report

Poole Lab

June 2022

Introduction

A survey was distributed electronically to Utah residents. The survey contained 10 sections assessing participants views and knowledge about HPV and vaccination. The first section of the survey contained questions about demographics, the second section was about where participants got their news. The third section assessed participants trust in government. The fourth section assessed participants trust in medicine. In the fifth section participants were asked about their religious practice. In the sixth section participants were asked about their aspirations for their children. In the seventh section participants were asked about their sexual attitudes and what they intend to teach their children about sex. The eighth and ninth section assessed participants knowledge about and HPV and attitudes towards vaccines. The final section contained questions assessing survey participants intent to vaccinate children against HPV. The survey contained 80 questions and took approximately 20 minutes to complete.

Population Demographics

A majority of survey participants were between 26 and 45 years old. A majority of survey participants were female. Most of the survey participants were White but all possible ethnic choices were represented in our sample population. More than half of the participants were married. Less than half of survey participants had children under 15, the recommended age for HPV vaccination. Less than half of survey participants have completed a college degree. The vast majority of households represented in our sample make less than $100,000 per year. The largest portion of participants work full time hourly followed by full time salaried and other. The largest segment of our sample population identify as republican followed by no political affiliation and Democrat. Our population is relatively centrist on both economic and social issues. A majority of survey participants self identified as Christian, the second largest sample segment indicated that they have no religious affiliation. Of the respondents who identified as christian the vast majority indicated that they are members of the Church of Jesus Christ of Latter-Day saints. Most respondents who indicated that they do not have a religious affiliation indicated that they are spiritual but not religious.
Participants were asked to rate five statements about HPV vaccination on a five point likert scale from strongly agree to strongly disagree. The majority of survey participants agreed or strongly agreed with the statements Vaccination would protect my child against HPV infection in the case of sexual assault, I will (or would) vaccinate both my sons and daughters against HPV, and I intend to vaccinate my children against HPV OR I have already vaccinated my children against HPV. The majority of survey participants disagreed or strongly disagreed with the statements Because HPV is sexually transmitted I will not vaccinate my children against it, and The potential side effects of the HPV vaccine will prevent me from vaccinating my children against HPV. The responses indicate that most of our sample population feel positively about HPV vaccination. Originally the CDC only recommended HPV vaccination for females, this does not appear to have affected the intent of our sample population to vaccinate both their sons and daughters. Most participants intend to vaccinate their children despite potential side effects. This could indicate that participants are more concerned about the potential harm HPV infection could cause then they are about potential side effects of vaccination. The HPV vaccines approved by the FDA have been extensively tested by for safety and there is a little risk of side effects; Most HPV infections are mild and are cleared naturally by the immune system, but the strains the vaccine protects against are considered high-risk and can cause various cancers including 99% or all cervical cancer cases. Most of the survey participants disagreeing with the idea of not vaccinating their children because HPV is sexually transmitted indicates that people are more concerned with the potential harm HPV can cause then its mode of transmission.
Participants were asked to rate seven statements about general vaccination on a five point likert scale from strongly agree to strongly disagree. The majority of survey participants agreed or strongly agreed with the statements Vaccination efforts have considerably reduced the transmission of infectious disease in the United States. My children are up to date on their recommended vaccines, Vaccines are extensively tested to ensure their safety, and Vaccines are more helpful than harmful. Participants opinions on the statements Vaccines contain dangerous toxins, and Vaccines often have severe side effects were more divided with the largest portion of participants indicating that they were unsure. The responses indicate that most of our sample population views vaccination positively but they are unsure about the risk of side-effects or what ingredients vaccines contain. It is encouraging to see that most respondents indicate that their children are up to date on their recommended vaccines. The majority of the sample population seems to feel that vaccines are both safe and effective based on their responses to the 1st, 4th, 5th, and 7th questions.
Almost all of the questions in the survey were combined to form a correlation matrix. Survey questions were compared to question 11.1 I intend to vaccinate my children against HPV, Or I have already vaccinated my children against HPV Questions 11.2 - 11.5 were excluded because they were designed to test attitudes about HPV vaccination and are therefore highly correlated. Free response questions were also removed. The numbers measure persons correlation coefficient, blue coloring indicates positive correlation, purple indicates negative correlation, blank squares indicate that the results were not significant (p-value > 0.05 chosen by convention). The bottom row of the matrix is question 11.1 intent to vaccinate.
A second correlation matrix was created by removing results that were not significantly correlated with question 11.1 intent to vaccinate
A third correlation matrix was created by selecting questions from the second correlation matrix that were negatively correlated with intent to vaccinate. In the smaller correlation matrix 40% of the questions were not significantly correlated with intent to vaccinate. Question text and numbers are listed in the table below. belief that natural remedies are as effective as prescription drugs and modern medical techniques is negatively correlated with intent to vaccinate. This could indicate that a segment of our sample population distrusts modern medicine. Frequency of scripture/holy text reading is negatively correlated with intent to vaccinate. No other measures of religiosity included in the survey were negatively correlated with intent to vaccinate and the correlation with frequency of reading holy texts/scripture is small, therefore if there is an impact on intent to vaccinate it is very small. Question 10.1.2 Vaccines often have severe side effects and question 10.1.5 Vaccines contain dangerous toxins had the strongest negative correlation with intent to vaccinate. This indicates that concerns about the safety of vaccines negatively impacts intent to vaccinate.

A fourth correlation matrix was created by selecting questions from the second matrix that were positively correlated with intent to vaccinate. Question text and number are listed in the table below. Political leanings on social and economic issues are moderately correlated with intent to vaccinate. Question 4.1.6 I trust in public health guidelines provided by local and state health departments. and question 4.1.7 I trust in public health guidelines provided by the CDC were both positively correlated with intent to vaccinate, but trust in CDC guidelines has a higher correlation coefficient. This could indicate that CDC guidelines have a greater impact on the decision to vaccinate then the guidelines provided by local and state health departments. Question 8.2 Sexual education is a necessary part of school curriculum was correlated with intent to vaccinate. This shows that participants who are concerned about HPV strive to protect their children against HPV through a variety of means including through education and vaccination. Concerns about sexually transmitted infection was positively correlated with intent to vaccinate. The HPV strains that the vaccine protects against are sexually transmitted, so it is unsurprising that respondents who are concerned about sexually transmitted infections have high intent to vaccinate. Questions 10.1.1 Vaccines are more helpful than harmful and question 10.1.3 Vaccines are effective at preventing disease were both found to be correlated with intent to vaccinate. This shows that general vaccine attitudes are one of the best predictors of intent to vaccinate, this corresponds to previous findings in our labs and by other researchers.

Darker blue indicates a higher intent to vaccinate and lighter blue indicates a lower intent to vaccinate, White counties indicate that no participants from that county participated in the survey.
